# 🏄‍♂️ WindsurfRules - Micro SaaS Starter Kit

*Core principles and conventions for Micro SaaS Starter Kit development*

## Project Context
The Micro SaaS Starter Kit (MSSK) is an opinionated boilerplate for indie hackers and small teams to bootstrap subscription-based SaaS products. It combines Go (Chi) backend, HTMX + Alpine.js frontend, Tailwind CSS, and Supabase-powered auth/PostgreSQL, deployed to Cloudflare's edge.

## Code Style and Structure
- Write concise, idiomatic Go code with proper error handling
- Use functional patterns; avoid unnecessary abstractions
- Follow standard Go project layout patterns
- Use descriptive variable names (e.g., isAuthenticated, hasSubscription)
- Structure repository files as follows:
  ```
  /cmd
    └─ api/main.go        # entrypoint for Go server
  /internal               # private application code
    ├─ auth/              # authentication related code
    ├─ config/            # configuration handling
    ├─ handler/           # HTTP handlers 
    ├─ middleware/        # application middleware
    ├─ model/             # domain models
    ├─ repository/        # data access
    └─ server/            # server configuration
  /migrations             # database migrations
  /sql                    # sqlc query files
  /web
    ├─ templates/         # HTML templates
    └─ static/            # static assets
  ```

## Tech Stack
- Go 1.22+
- Chi router
- HTMX 1.x
- Alpine.js 3.x
- Tailwind CSS 3.x
- PostgreSQL 15 (Supabase)
- Golang-migrate
- SQLC
- Cloudflare Pages/Workers

## Naming Conventions
- Use lowercase with underscores for Go files (e.g., `user_handler.go`)
- Favor descriptive package names over cute names
- Use PascalCase for exported functions/types (e.g., `UserHandler`)
- Use camelCase for unexported functions/variables (e.g., `validateUser()`)
- Follow `cmd/internal/pkg` convention for package structure

## Go Usage
- Use Go 1.22+ for all code
- Leverage standard library when possible
- Create interfaces only when needed for testing/abstraction
- Use context for cancellation/timeout/request scoping
- Handle errors explicitly; avoid panics
- Use absolute imports for all packages
- Implement proper error handling with helpful messages
- Use explicit return types for all functions

## Web Development Specific
- Use Chi's router groups for feature organization
- Implement proper middleware stack in correct order
- Use HTMX for dynamic UI updates
- Use Alpine.js only when necessary for client-side interactivity
- Implement progressive enhancement (work without JS)
- Leverage html/template with proper escaping
- Follow REST API conventions for endpoints

## State Management
- Use Supabase for authentication state
- Implement proper JWT validation
- Use PostgreSQL for persistent data
- Implement proper cleanup in HTTP handlers

## Syntax and Formatting
- Follow `gofmt` standards
- Use table-driven tests
- Implement consistent error handling patterns
- Keep handler functions focused and short
- Separate business logic from HTTP handling

## UI and Styling
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling
- Implement responsive design principles
- Create reusable HTMX patterns
- Follow accessibility guidelines
- Keep UI components minimal and focused

## Error Handling
- Implement global error middleware
- Return appropriate HTTP status codes
- Log errors with relevant context
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Implement proper validation feedback

## Testing
- Write table-driven tests for utilities and handlers
- Implement integration tests for critical flows
- Test database interactions with real PostgreSQL
- Use mocks only when necessary
- Test both success and error paths

## Security
- Implement proper JWT validation
- Use CSRF protection for state-changing operations
- Implement rate limiting for sensitive endpoints
- Configure secure headers
- Sanitize all user inputs
- Use Row Level Security in Supabase
- Follow OWASP security practices

## Git Usage
Commit Message Prefixes:
- `fix:` for bug fixes
- `feat:` for new features
- `perf:` for performance improvements
- `docs:` for documentation changes
- `style:` for formatting changes
- `refactor:` for code refactoring
- `test:` for adding missing tests
- `chore:` for maintenance tasks

Rules:
- Use lowercase for commit messages
- Keep the summary line concise
- Reference issue numbers when applicable
- Follow conventional commits specification

## Documentation
- Maintain clear README with setup instructions
- Document API endpoints and request/response formats
- Keep migrations well-documented
- Add comments for complex business logic
- Document environment variables

## Development Workflow
- Use Taskfile (or Make) for common operations
- Follow phase-based development approach
- Implement proper code review process
- Test in multiple environments
- Follow semantic versioning for releases
- Establish clear exit criteria for each phase
